<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="40" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,1061,1407]" pageId="13" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,279,1061,1087]" pageId="13" pageNumber="40">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Length of male 
<quantity box="[470,563,1061,1087]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6" pageId="13" pageNumber="40" unit="mm" value="2.6">2.6 mm</quantity>
, female 
<quantity box="[660,752,1061,1087]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.1" pageId="13" pageNumber="40" unit="mm" value="3.1">3.1 mm</quantity>
. Closely resembling 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dietrich &amp; Dmitriev" authorityYear="2007" box="[996,1195,1061,1086]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Neozygina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argentiniensis">
<emphasis box="[996,1195,1061,1086]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="40">N. argentiniensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differing as follows: pygofer with dorsal appendage extended to apex; aedeagal shaft (
<figureCitation box="[1030,1168,1101,1127]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="14.[151,255,1563,1587]" captionTargetBox="[278,1261,789,1525]" captionTargetId="figure-314@14.[275,1312,789,1539]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 4. New South American spp. of Neozygina, male pygofer (A, D, G, N), aedeagus in lateral (B, E, H, J, L, O) and posterior (C, F, I, K, M, P) views. A–C, N. abancayensis; D–F, N. argentiniensis; G–I, N. asymmetrica; J–K, N. expanda; L–M, N. forcipata; N–P, N. retrorsa." pageId="13" pageNumber="40">Figs. 4J, K</figureCitation>
) in lateral view more strongly divergent from dorsal apodeme and with posterior margin evenly curved, processes formed by bifid apex strongly expanded and convergent distally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
